From Hans Geurtsen Subject Cursors According to the OSF Motif Style Guide one should use cursor shapes to give the user a visual clue of what is happening or what is expected of So a hourglass cursor should be shown when the application is busy or a caution cursor should be shown over an area when input is expected in Defining cursors for widgets has to be done at rather low So defining a cursor for all widgets in an application but not for a certain subpart of it is a rather complicated When cursors have been defined for some windows a crosswire cursor for a DrawingArea things get even more My intuition says that things should be easier but is this so If anyone has a solid and complete solution to my problem please let me The topics on busy cursors in the several FAQ's are not helpful since they only work for applications where all windows have the cursor window attribute set to 'None' Hans Geurtsen Phone Nucletron Research e mail Surface Waardgelder NL TH Veenendaal